<subSubSection id="B96D8515C93C93A84D67023D789C92A1" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="typification">
<paragraph id="9C59B3D0A673F44904D26840929C2F0C" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Typification.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="93686E9F8211FA2976BCC8F11FDC03B8" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Thailand, Chiang Mai, Chiang Dao District, Ban Huathung; 19°420'N, 98°971'E; on 
<taxonomicName id="CEA3F36A8F6ECC8DD5A6138A9DBB6EC2" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Cordycipitaceae" genus="Gibellula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="" order="Araneida" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="order">Araneida</taxonomicName>
attached to the underside of unidentified dicot leaf; 5 October 2012; K. Tasanathai, A. Khonsanit, W. Noisripoom, P. Srikitikulchai, R. Promharn (Holotype no. BBH 32918, ex-type culture no. BCC 56802, isolated from conidia) GenBank: ITS = MT477070, LSU = MT477063, 
<emphasis id="9E5E3EA04209C9B46957E4DE47AF708D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">TEF1</emphasis>
= MT503329, 
<emphasis id="969AD318928F0E0FB45CBEE2B3BBE82B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">RPB1</emphasis>
= MT503322, 
<emphasis id="CD8009EBA8EB2D9237E86690EA4F30E7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">RPB2</emphasis>
= MT503337.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5DFB66D21A4A57A6A2B9CC16295457E0" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2F2C2C9FCA7144B9E40CB9E133A154D5" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B7C23A5BB0F9509A93036A4341545F2" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Refers to the fusiform part-spores.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AB28955C68B6317856CAE63A7B012798" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph id="95D5DE5AD0552C9A588C7340BCE3EFF5" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5EF8332AF2606F838637BA6597AD578D" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Spiders totally covered by the white to cream mycelial mat. A single synnema or synnemata in pairs cream to light brown, often darker than the mycelia covering the host, narrowing toward the apex and terminating in a swollen sterile tip with acute apex (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C92C97866AFAB3018937C7B6CA20E107" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Gibellula fusiformispora a fungus on a spider (BBH 38838) b fungus on a spider (BBH 32918) c synnemata (BBH 32918) d, e perithecia (BBH 38838) f ascus (BBH 38838) g ascospores (BBH 38838) h conidia (BBH 32918) i conidiophores showing conidial heads (BBH 32918) j conidial head bearing conidia (BCC 32918) k colonies obverse and reverse on PDA at 25 ° C after 20 days. Scale bars: 250 μm (e); 100 μm (i); 50 μm (g); 20 μm (f, h, j)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.72.55088.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448317" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">3a-c</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="8CC7930180D2E341A234B583B6FCE3DD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Conidiophores</emphasis>
arising laterally from the outer layer of synnemata, crowded, (23-)31-53(-83) 
<normalizedToken id="DA8091698D9B9904C7618E9188897A44" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(4-)5.5-6.5(-7.5) 
<normalizedToken id="08B40D6A75BC31B84DFD4B0D559D84AB" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, mostly verrucose, occasionally slightly roughed for very short conidiophores, abruptly narrowing to a slender apex and forming a globose to subglobose vesicle (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="363AE12FDE861120EA59238F840776C8" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Gibellula fusiformispora a fungus on a spider (BBH 38838) b fungus on a spider (BBH 32918) c synnemata (BBH 32918) d, e perithecia (BBH 38838) f ascus (BBH 38838) g ascospores (BBH 38838) h conidia (BBH 32918) i conidiophores showing conidial heads (BBH 32918) j conidial head bearing conidia (BCC 32918) k colonies obverse and reverse on PDA at 25 ° C after 20 days. Scale bars: 250 μm (e); 100 μm (i); 50 μm (g); 20 μm (f, h, j)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.72.55088.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448317" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">3c, i</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="511436C904BF819A30364CAA632E1801" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Vesicles</emphasis>
6-7(-8) 
<normalizedToken id="164FF5068649309AD57BAE60F8CDC8B2" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in diam, each bearing a number of metulae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CCB9386865544111DC7FB7F25A3ADAAE" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Gibellula fusiformispora a fungus on a spider (BBH 38838) b fungus on a spider (BBH 32918) c synnemata (BBH 32918) d, e perithecia (BBH 38838) f ascus (BBH 38838) g ascospores (BBH 38838) h conidia (BBH 32918) i conidiophores showing conidial heads (BBH 32918) j conidial head bearing conidia (BCC 32918) k colonies obverse and reverse on PDA at 25 ° C after 20 days. Scale bars: 250 μm (e); 100 μm (i); 50 μm (g); 20 μm (f, h, j)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.72.55088.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448317" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">3j</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="0A1637DC5C998F3D80C283B7DB6B2CA0" genus="Metulae" lsidName="Metulae" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="581DEACE0227DD6BDF0822442BECB21D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Metulae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
obovoid to broadly obovoid, (7-)7.5-9(-10) 
<normalizedToken id="AD3714E833FA52EF721DFF0424CFFB85" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(4.5-)5-5.5(-6) 
<normalizedToken id="2D6C016119186BBBA14183479D535415" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2560C851D9578C85257B48AD102DDBF4" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Gibellula fusiformispora a fungus on a spider (BBH 38838) b fungus on a spider (BBH 32918) c synnemata (BBH 32918) d, e perithecia (BBH 38838) f ascus (BBH 38838) g ascospores (BBH 38838) h conidia (BBH 32918) i conidiophores showing conidial heads (BBH 32918) j conidial head bearing conidia (BCC 32918) k colonies obverse and reverse on PDA at 25 ° C after 20 days. Scale bars: 250 μm (e); 100 μm (i); 50 μm (g); 20 μm (f, h, j)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.72.55088.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448317" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">3j</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="F5158691F5646E29AFD4C4FF930287F3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Phialides</emphasis>
borne on metulae, narrowly obovoid, 7-8.5(-10) 
<normalizedToken id="86C25C7AEDC0B5A00FF536CA39542CCB" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-3 
<normalizedToken id="72407B9FBF3E8696EF6229BC5A00E864" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
bearing fusiform to broadly fusiform conidia, (3.5-)4-5(-6) 
<normalizedToken id="888F74D90115C879977FE6343901729F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5-2(-2.5) 
<normalizedToken id="4AFBEEB404A53EA214B57F9F47206E84" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6189B419972E1E80796C9F1269E86BB6" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Gibellula fusiformispora a fungus on a spider (BBH 38838) b fungus on a spider (BBH 32918) c synnemata (BBH 32918) d, e perithecia (BBH 38838) f ascus (BBH 38838) g ascospores (BBH 38838) h conidia (BBH 32918) i conidiophores showing conidial heads (BBH 32918) j conidial head bearing conidia (BCC 32918) k colonies obverse and reverse on PDA at 25 ° C after 20 days. Scale bars: 250 μm (e); 100 μm (i); 50 μm (g); 20 μm (f, h, j)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.72.55088.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448317" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">3h, j</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="43DE8A3D9AE42967F45E4776C2EB31FB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Conidial heads</emphasis>
spherical, (31-)32-34.5(-37) 
<normalizedToken id="94DF89435E7FAE0E6174DF293289C571" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in diam (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9EDA428382135ACE2E7B1C4596F01F47" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Gibellula fusiformispora a fungus on a spider (BBH 38838) b fungus on a spider (BBH 32918) c synnemata (BBH 32918) d, e perithecia (BBH 38838) f ascus (BBH 38838) g ascospores (BBH 38838) h conidia (BBH 32918) i conidiophores showing conidial heads (BBH 32918) j conidial head bearing conidia (BCC 32918) k colonies obverse and reverse on PDA at 25 ° C after 20 days. Scale bars: 250 μm (e); 100 μm (i); 50 μm (g); 20 μm (f, h, j)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.72.55088.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448317" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">3j</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="C05246160CE0609E5E844DA77EF5E70E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Perithecia</emphasis>
mostly appearing in pairs, ovoid, superficial with a loose covering of white to cream mycelia, reddish yellow, up to 1,000 
<normalizedToken id="138B59E9C2DB72C378E3777E1237D33B" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in length, 320-350 
<normalizedToken id="52F8BED2ECC5EA722418C968A23DDCFF" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in width (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="84BAC0315BEF1A7EF4ECC1A4CCC44C53" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Gibellula fusiformispora a fungus on a spider (BBH 38838) b fungus on a spider (BBH 32918) c synnemata (BBH 32918) d, e perithecia (BBH 38838) f ascus (BBH 38838) g ascospores (BBH 38838) h conidia (BBH 32918) i conidiophores showing conidial heads (BBH 32918) j conidial head bearing conidia (BCC 32918) k colonies obverse and reverse on PDA at 25 ° C after 20 days. Scale bars: 250 μm (e); 100 μm (i); 50 μm (g); 20 μm (f, h, j)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.72.55088.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448317" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">3d-e</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="94B823F9540FF6F0730EE454D0572AD1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Asci</emphasis>
600-700 
<normalizedToken id="A5D7C24935E6618F5F9B0A1172F9D981" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
7-8 
<normalizedToken id="AFD9614E9F12DD5C7B0FCAF96B72D32D" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DCB0196D3F157284F81A28A7596A4F12" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Gibellula fusiformispora a fungus on a spider (BBH 38838) b fungus on a spider (BBH 32918) c synnemata (BBH 32918) d, e perithecia (BBH 38838) f ascus (BBH 38838) g ascospores (BBH 38838) h conidia (BBH 32918) i conidiophores showing conidial heads (BBH 32918) j conidial head bearing conidia (BCC 32918) k colonies obverse and reverse on PDA at 25 ° C after 20 days. Scale bars: 250 μm (e); 100 μm (i); 50 μm (g); 20 μm (f, h, j)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.72.55088.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448317" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">3f</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="AEC4505AEF7BEB1667197D6833043505" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Ascospores</emphasis>
often disarticulating into part-spores. 
<emphasis id="F7ABEB6EFEB17E4C45BF21288CF75DEA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Part-spores</emphasis>
fusiform, 12-15 
<normalizedToken id="A1354C162BF6329AA147BAE4055D551B" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-3 
